## MANUFACTURING PHILOSOPHY

Here's the thing most people get wrong about how a stealth bomber gets built: they picture a factory floor. One building, one assembly line, wings moving down a track toward a tail section.

That's the 777 model. And it's not what's happening in Palmdale.

Picture the floor at Palmdale, and picture Charleston, not Everett. Not thousands of rivets going in one at a time along a slow-moving line — a small number of massive, pre-finished sections, arriving whole, lowered into place, and joined. Six major sections instead of two composite barrels, but the same underlying logic: the hard work already happened somewhere else. What's left at final assembly isn't fabrication. It's convergence.

Officially, it's called Modular Open Systems Architecture. Unofficially — this is a Kubernetes bird. Not one interdependent code blob, but modules, capsules, pieces that can be revised and re-incorporated into the whole without touching everything else around them.

These aren't confirmed changes between airframes, worth being clear about: the inlet geometry, the missing pitot boom, the sensor windows, the cockpit finish — these are spotter observations, pieced together from released photos, not something Northrop or the Air Force has put on the record. Even the public differences between airframe 1 and 2 have to be reconstructed by outsiders looking at pixels, because the program simply doesn't explain itself.

We know the pool of suppliers. We don't know who does what — and that's by design. The Air Force is keeping this one better hidden than they kept the B-2's supply chain thirty years ago. It is what it is.

