## THE NUMBERS

It is what it is, and the detail matters. Twenty-one aircraft funded under the current production lots. Four and a half billion dollars committed to expand the line. And Northrop — not the taxpayer — has already absorbed more than two billion dollars in losses getting to this point, the price of a fixed-price contract signed a decade before the design was even mature. On top of that, Northrop is putting a further two and a half billion of its own money into expanding production capacity now.

*[SPECULATION — flagged]* Depending on how the accounting actually works — something the public record doesn't spell out — funds may have been committed for as few as fifteen additional airframes, or as many as twenty-seven aircraft total. Nobody outside the program has said which.

