## WHEN "OPERATIONAL" ISN'T OPERATIONAL

One aircraft is expected on the ramp at Ellsworth in 2027 — not new production, but a converted test jet.

*[SPECULATION — flagged]* Call it a year and a half to two years for that conversion. Not because anyone's said so — nobody has — but because the industry's own history, from Boeing's own multi-year 787 rework years, says these things rarely move as fast as the press release promises. A second conversion, call it a year — shorter, on the logic that whatever's learned doing the first doesn't have to be relearned on the second.

Becoming operational isn't just removing test instrumentation. It's weapons integration, electronic warfare certification, nuclear certification — and some of what it's supposed to carry, like the LRSO cruise missile, isn't even in production yet. "On the ramp at Ellsworth in 2027" and "combat-ready" are not the same sentence.

The Air Force is still certifying new weapons for the F-16 — an aircraft that entered service in 1979. Full weapons certification isn't a milestone a platform hits and moves past. It's a permanent condition of owning the aircraft. Whatever the B-21 carries at initial operational capability will be a fraction of what it eventually carries — and "eventually" doesn't have a fixed end date.

